{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527747"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14220"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14220"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.12,0.15,0.33,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55160"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6906"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14220"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40678"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1378"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45747"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55160"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a single episode of syncope that occurred while he was walking. He regained consciousness spontaneously after about one minute. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His regular medications include metformin, perindopril, and aspirin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 60/min and regular, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals normal heart sounds with no murmurs. An ECG shows left bundle branch block with a PR interval of 220 ms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Echocardiogram","Electrophysiological study","Temporary pacing","24-hour Holter monitor","Tilt table testing"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with syncope and an ECG showing left bundle branch block (LBBB) with a prolonged PR interval, raising concern for potential progression to complete heart block. In this scenario, the most appropriate next step is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E. An echocardiogram is crucial to assess for structural heart abnormalities such as left ventricular dysfunction, aortic stenosis, or hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy. These findings would significantly influence management decisions, including the choice between a pacemaker, cardiac resynchronization therapy (CRT), or an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (ICD).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour Holter monitor\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in detecting intermittent arrhythmias and heart block. However, given the presence of LBBB on the 12-lead ECG with syncope, this may not be the most appropriate first-line step and could delay diagnosis of structural heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eelectrophysiological study\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive test that can be performed as a second-line investigation to assess for conduction disease if the left ventricular function is found to be normal on echocardiogram. It is not typically the first step in evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETilt table testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose vasovagal syncope, but it is not indicated as the first step in a patient with concerning ECG changes suggesting a cardiac cause of syncope.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporary pacing\u003C/strong\u003E is not required at this stage as the patient has only had a single episode of syncope and is currently stable. It would be considered if the patient had recurrent syncope or if there was evidence of complete heart block.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of syncope and new LBBB, especially with a prolonged PR interval, suggests a high risk of progression to complete heart block. To decide on the type of device (if needed), the first point of investigation should be an echocardiogram. If the echocardiogram shows normal left ventricular function, the patient may then proceed to an electrophysiological study for further evaluation of the conduction system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Left bundle branch block (LBBB) with syncope requires urgent evaluation for potential cardiac causes, including complete heart block.","An echocardiogram is crucial in determining structural heart abnormalities and guiding management decisions in patients with LBBB and syncope.","Further investigations such as electrophysiological study may be considered based on echocardiogram findings and clinical course."],"references":["Glikson M, Nielsen JC, Kronborg MB, Michowitz Y, Auricchio A, Barbash IM, et al. 2021 ESC Guidelines on cardiac pacing and cardiac resynchronization therapy. Eur Heart J. 2021 Sep 14;42(35):3427-3520. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34455430/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40678"}},"question":{"data